WEBVTT

00:04.258 --> 00:05.440
Welcome to Gospel in Life.

00:06.101 --> 00:13.773
In his first letter to early Christians, Peter tells believers they must grow up in their salvation, much like children maturing into adulthood.

00:14.233 --> 00:17.418
But what does it really look like to grow in our faith?

00:17.438 --> 00:27.474
Today, Tim Keller invites us to consider the lifelong journey of maturing spiritually and how we move toward a life that's deeply rooted in the redeeming work of Jesus Christ.

00:27.810 --> 00:33.382
After you listen, we invite you to go online to gospelandlife.com and sign up for our email updates.

00:33.863 --> 00:41.118
When you sign up, you'll receive our quarterly journal with stories of gospel changed lives, as well as other valuable gospel-centered resources.

00:41.539 --> 00:43.844
Subscribe today at gospelandlife.com.

00:44.385 --> 00:46.770
Now, here's Tim Keller with today's teaching.

00:54.114 --> 01:02.346
In your bulletin, you have printed a passage of the Scripture, the Bible, and that's what we're going to look at again tonight for the fourth time, the last time.

01:02.767 --> 01:11.259
Whenever I go through a passage of the Bible and we stop on it and we look at it and I finally say, we've been in it long enough, tonight's the night, we're going to stop.

01:12.181 --> 01:13.703
At the end of this, we're going to move on.

01:14.324 --> 01:17.649
This means I have too much material to cover, which always happens.

01:18.230 --> 01:24.018
So we are going to try to show you the basic features, a kind of overview of it.

01:24.514 --> 01:31.842
But this passage, let me analyze it for you for a second before we read it, just so you see how it works.

01:31.982 --> 01:32.863
It's a sandwich.

01:33.384 --> 01:34.886
It's a very tall big sandwich.

01:34.906 --> 01:36.387
It's got five layers to it.

01:37.248 --> 01:43.836
And what Peter's really trying to get at is he's trying to get people, we looked at this two weeks ago, to love one another.

01:45.438 --> 01:52.786
But he knows, he's not naive, he's not so stupid as to think, that just simply exhorting people to love each other will be enough.

01:52.994 --> 02:01.347
He says, you won't be able to love each other unless you draw on a power greater than yourself, unless you learn to draw on a supernatural power.

02:01.948 --> 02:05.814
And so what he actually does is he starts out by saying, draw on that power.

02:06.135 --> 02:07.237
Then he says, love one another.

02:07.577 --> 02:09.721
Then he says, and draw on that power.

02:09.781 --> 02:11.103
Then he says, love one another.

02:11.143 --> 02:14.168
And then he says, and don't forget to draw on that power.

02:14.608 --> 02:18.194
Like any good teacher, any good preacher, he repeats himself constantly.

02:18.402 --> 02:46.418
And and that's what you see the layers is first of all he says in verse 22 Read with me now that you have purified yourselves by obeying the truth so that you have sincere love for your brothers love one another deeply From the heart See drawing that power see you purified yourselves by obeying the truth love one other deeply then he goes on for you have been born again and

02:46.690 --> 02:51.396
Not of perishable seed, but of imperishable, through the living and enduring word of God.

02:51.937 --> 02:55.502
For all men are like grass, and all their glory is like the flowers of the field.

02:55.982 --> 03:01.009
The grass withers and the flowers fall, but the word of the Lord abides forever."

03:01.950 --> 03:04.474
Again, now he's back to drawing that power.

03:04.934 --> 03:06.777
You've been born again, imperishable seed.

03:07.077 --> 03:16.530
But then, look, verse 1, therefore, now he's back to love one another, rid yourselves of all malice and all deceit, hypocrisy, envy, and slander of every kind.

03:16.770 --> 03:27.243
like newborn babies crave pure spiritual milk so that by it you may grow up in your salvation now that you have tasted that the Lord is good.

03:28.846 --> 03:29.747
This is God's word.

03:31.108 --> 03:41.582
So, what we're looking at here tonight is this passage in which Peter says, as newborn babes, grow up in your salvation.

03:41.922 --> 03:42.403
Grow up.

03:42.783 --> 03:44.786
Being a Christian is not a static thing.

03:44.898 --> 03:45.539
It's a journey.

03:45.579 --> 03:51.005
Being a Christian is not simply a static thing, rather it's an adventure.

03:52.586 --> 04:06.041
And what we're going to do is just look here at how this passage gives us why we should be growing as Christians, what we should be growing into as Christians, and how we should be growing as Christians.

04:06.822 --> 04:08.583
Why, what, and how?

04:09.705 --> 04:14.770
Now, last week we really got into the why, and let me actually in a sense conclude by

04:14.978 --> 04:18.222
for those of you who were here last week and just summarized for those of you who weren't.

04:19.103 --> 04:20.164
Why should we grow?

04:20.245 --> 04:21.967
Grow up, he says.

04:21.987 --> 04:22.828
Why?

04:22.848 --> 04:26.893
And the answer is because you're stupid.

04:30.057 --> 04:30.778
You're infants.

04:31.639 --> 04:32.460
You're babies.

04:33.121 --> 04:35.103
Because you're newborn babies, you need to grow up.

04:35.163 --> 04:43.954
Now, last week we said, and let me summarize this again, how important it is, if you don't understand the absolute imperative nature of growth,

04:44.514 --> 04:57.811
If you don't yearn to grow, if you don't see yourself as stupid, as foolish, as young, as a baby, you don't understand really the nature of the Christian faith and the nature of the Christian life.

04:59.473 --> 05:11.308
One of the things that's very hard, especially in a place like New York, is that as usual, non-Christian thought is always much more naive and simplistic than Christian thought.

05:11.849 --> 05:12.690
That's a principle.

05:12.898 --> 05:16.022
The Christian truth is always more complex.

05:16.042 --> 05:25.656
People think that if you're more talented than others, if you're better looking than others, if you're more accomplished than others, if you've done better in life than others, if you've been more successful than others, somehow you're a better person.

05:27.478 --> 05:28.280
That's not true at all.

05:29.481 --> 05:34.128
In the same way, people think if you're having a messed up life and everything's going wrong for you, somehow you must be a worse person.

05:34.528 --> 05:35.630
That's not true at all either.

05:36.070 --> 05:39.395
Ah, the reality is far more complex, the Bible says.

05:39.796 --> 05:41.458
Do you remember the movie Amadeus?

05:42.274 --> 05:47.119
And the basic problem in the movie is here's Salieri, a good and decent man.

05:47.639 --> 05:55.728
And here is Amadeus Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, who is an absolute snook, an obnoxious child of a man.

05:56.588 --> 06:01.533
And Salieri can't figure out if I'm so much more of a good person, why is that he's so much more talented?

06:02.114 --> 06:02.835
He can't figure it out.

06:02.875 --> 06:10.162
The Bible says that God, in order to make the world a far better place than it has the right to be,

06:10.242 --> 06:12.124
a far better place to live than it ought to be.

06:12.164 --> 06:24.057
He just throws out gifts of brilliance and of artistic ability and of ability and aptitude and intelligence.

06:24.318 --> 06:31.345
He throws those gifts out the way a gardener would throw flour seed onto a bank, just to beautify it.

06:31.546 --> 06:32.567
He just throws it out there.

06:33.568 --> 06:39.154
And therefore, lots and lots of people who are not particularly good people and certainly

06:39.362 --> 06:43.368
But not on the basis of what you believe or you don't believe, God just gives these gifts out.

06:44.090 --> 06:45.672
Now here's why it's so hard.

06:46.473 --> 06:50.320
If and when you become a Christian, you might be awfully smart.

06:51.081 --> 06:53.945
You might be smarter than most of the other people at the church that you're attending.

06:54.406 --> 06:55.448
You might be very gifted.

06:55.468 --> 06:58.373
You might be much more successful, but you're still a baby.

06:59.935 --> 07:06.706
You start out as an infant spiritually, and it's very hard to understand, and it's very hard to explain, and it's very hard to even grasp.

07:06.786 --> 07:08.850
Nobody wants to think of themselves as babies.

07:08.870 --> 07:10.773
They like to think of themselves as fairly able people.

07:11.054 --> 07:14.640
They like to think that somehow they've been quite...

07:14.660 --> 07:19.288
The average New Yorker who finally becomes a Christian actually feels, boy, I'm pretty special.

07:19.308 --> 07:20.190
I'm looking in the crowd.

07:21.332 --> 07:24.938
I must be pretty insightful that I've discovered these things that other people haven't discovered.

07:24.999 --> 07:28.244
Most of my friends think I'm crazy, but I have found the truth.

07:28.625 --> 07:30.248
And you think well of yourself, you shouldn't.

07:30.548 --> 07:31.410
You're a baby.

07:32.066 --> 07:33.227
It doesn't matter your IQ.

07:33.267 --> 07:34.569
It doesn't matter your bank account.

07:34.589 --> 07:35.891
It doesn't matter how accomplished you are.

07:35.911 --> 07:36.471
You're a baby.

07:36.491 --> 07:37.513
We all start as babies.

07:38.974 --> 07:39.595
You don't believe it.

07:40.737 --> 07:48.767
Let me just give you a couple of characteristics of babies, of little children, and just show you how this is also the characteristics of the typical Christian.

07:50.108 --> 07:51.910
And that's why most Christians are babies.

07:51.950 --> 07:53.352
Most of us are spiritual babies.

07:53.412 --> 07:54.954
Most of us haven't even gotten out of that.

07:56.055 --> 08:01.362
Now, I mentioned some of these at the very end of last week, but let me give you a little more of a treatment of them for

08:01.922 --> 08:04.447
Little children, first of all, are unstable.

08:05.991 --> 08:10.841
First they'll be just... Have you ever seen this children just crying and crying and you say, let's get some ice cream?

08:10.941 --> 08:11.222
Okay.

08:11.783 --> 08:12.364
And they're fine.

08:12.404 --> 08:13.366
They're just fine.

08:13.967 --> 08:14.869
All the tears are gone.

08:14.909 --> 08:15.350
Why?

08:15.370 --> 08:17.435
Because they're shallow.

08:18.216 --> 08:19.118
I'm not trying to be nasty.

08:19.138 --> 08:20.261
There's not that much to them.

08:20.942 --> 08:22.866
You know, their sorrow can only go so deep.

08:23.458 --> 08:24.899
And because there's only so much of them.

08:25.140 --> 08:26.141
How sorrowful can they be?

08:26.681 --> 08:28.403
But then on the other hand, their joy only goes so far.

08:28.423 --> 08:29.404
And they go back and forth.

08:29.904 --> 08:31.065
They're very, very unstable.

08:31.085 --> 08:31.906
They go all around.

08:31.946 --> 08:33.487
They go in every direction.

08:33.968 --> 08:37.651
Those of you who have have children, those of you who have even spent any time with children, you know that's true.

08:38.272 --> 08:39.313
They're highly unstable.

08:39.433 --> 08:40.514
And they jump all around.

08:40.534 --> 08:41.235
They move all around.

08:41.755 --> 08:43.777
So look at the average Christian.

08:43.877 --> 08:44.758
Or look at yourself.

08:46.139 --> 08:49.883
Do you find, as long as everything is going well, oh, God loves me.

08:50.143 --> 08:53.426
And as soon as things start to go poorly, why has God done this to me?

08:53.922 --> 08:55.524
How could God be so cruel to me?

08:55.624 --> 08:57.166
In vain, I have washed my hands.

08:57.226 --> 08:58.768
In vain, I have kept my heart pure.

08:59.048 --> 09:00.410
What good am I getting out of it?

09:00.430 --> 09:01.852
I've been a Christian now for six months.

09:02.152 --> 09:04.795
And look, I'm doing more poorly financially.

09:04.815 --> 09:07.679
I'm doing poorly financially.

09:07.699 --> 09:08.299
You're excited?

09:08.540 --> 09:09.821
Then you get all cast down.

09:10.802 --> 09:12.284
Well, you get real excited after a sermon.

09:12.304 --> 09:14.567
You say, I'm really going to do something about it and you forget all about it.

09:15.688 --> 09:18.191
You read a book and you have all these resolutions and they're all broken.

09:18.652 --> 09:20.734
Tears of repentance, you never do anything about it.

09:20.995 --> 09:21.735
You're a child.

09:22.757 --> 09:23.858
That's all right.

09:24.002 --> 09:25.644
Everybody starts out as a child.

09:26.164 --> 09:31.089
Except Adam, he was, you know, the day after he was born evidently, he looked like he was 30 years old.

09:31.129 --> 09:36.254
But apart from him, apart from him, we all have to start out that way.

09:37.875 --> 09:38.656
Children unstable.

09:38.756 --> 09:41.559
Secondly, children are self-centered.

09:44.101 --> 09:47.825
Children really, children have to be taught not to interrupt.

09:48.325 --> 09:50.247
It really doesn't matter what anybody else is talking about.

09:50.527 --> 09:53.330
When they want your attention, they just want it.

09:54.082 --> 10:00.654
They have a lot of trouble concentrating on anything that's not them for a very long period of time.

10:00.995 --> 10:07.487
If you're having a conversation with a child, it'll go on for at least 30 or 40 seconds, and then the child will say, well, enough about you.

10:07.547 --> 10:08.669
What do you think of my new shoes?

10:09.390 --> 10:10.372
That's the way children are.

10:10.412 --> 10:14.800
In the same way, look at yourself.

10:15.321 --> 10:17.906
Do you find yourself constantly getting your feelings hurt?

10:18.338 --> 10:19.239
Children are like that.

10:19.599 --> 10:22.422
Children don't understand why people don't drop everything to meet their needs.

10:22.823 --> 10:29.009
People don't understand why children don't understand why people don't drop everything and move heaven and earth.

10:29.790 --> 10:31.371
Change their schedules to meet their needs.

10:31.391 --> 10:32.312
That's the way children are.

10:32.773 --> 10:35.956
You expect children to be that way, but that's how you start off as Christians.

10:37.297 --> 10:38.698
You're always getting bent out of shape.

10:38.738 --> 10:41.201
You're always feeling people aren't noticing me.

10:41.581 --> 10:43.623
You're always feeling people are mistreating me.

10:44.384 --> 10:46.226
This is the typical church, by the way.

10:46.626 --> 10:49.329
filled with people who are always getting their feelings hurt with each other.

10:49.809 --> 10:51.491
Always feeling I'm being misused.

10:51.831 --> 10:56.215
Always wondering why everybody doesn't drop everything they're doing and huddle around them and meet their needs.

10:56.776 --> 11:01.801
That's a typical church because the typical Christian is a baby but doesn't realize it.

11:02.682 --> 11:06.125
Doesn't realize that unless I do something about it, I'm going to stay here for a long time.

11:06.706 --> 11:07.246
I want to move out.

11:07.606 --> 11:10.669
Children are, we said, number one, unstable.

11:10.690 --> 11:12.111
Number two, children are self-centered.

11:12.792 --> 11:14.653
Are you unstable?

11:14.733 --> 11:15.314
Are you?

11:16.002 --> 11:16.623
She's self-centered.

11:17.584 --> 11:21.090
Third, children have very short attention spans.

11:22.111 --> 11:22.652
Very short.

11:23.453 --> 11:29.202
If you take a child to a movie, one of the things that's so bad, you take a child to a movie and you just hope there's lots of action in it.

11:29.683 --> 11:30.324
You just hope.

11:30.845 --> 11:36.073
And unfortunately, you know, me start out with a lot of action and then next thing you know, oh my gosh, plot development, character development.

11:36.093 --> 11:42.322
And you know the kids will be jumping all around because they will have to fill up the lack of action with their own.

11:42.690 --> 11:45.314
Children have very short attention spans.

11:45.454 --> 11:49.861
Everything you say to them has to be really exciting, colorful, quick.

11:49.881 --> 11:54.228
That's the reason why even when they're real little, you start to talk to them in an exaggerated way.

11:54.248 --> 11:56.531
You have to say, hi there.

11:56.912 --> 11:57.733
How are you doing?

11:58.114 --> 11:59.556
Why do you talk that way to kids?

11:59.676 --> 12:01.359
Why do you automatically talk that way to kids?

12:01.379 --> 12:05.084
Because you can't keep their attention if you just talk naturally and normally.

12:06.166 --> 12:08.690
Now Paul, in 1 Corinthians,

12:09.538 --> 12:12.743
talks to a whole church full of babies, and he says, you want miracles.

12:13.865 --> 12:14.907
You want quick answers.

12:15.668 --> 12:17.291
You want God to come through like that.

12:18.272 --> 12:18.873
You're babies.

12:19.715 --> 12:27.307
Mature people, mature Christians, their emphasis is on character, on discipline, on truth, on righteousness.

12:27.527 --> 12:28.569
They want to hear the truth.

12:28.789 --> 12:36.562
And they are willing to understand that Christianity is a long obedience in the same direction.

12:36.866 --> 12:40.269
Christianity is studying the word of God and getting it deep into yourself.

12:40.970 --> 12:45.354
Christianity is doing your duty even when your feelings are flat.

12:45.394 --> 12:46.696
We talked about that last week.

12:47.116 --> 12:49.498
Only children, everything's gotta be exciting all the time.

12:50.319 --> 12:52.101
As soon as something is boring, off it goes.

12:52.521 --> 12:53.762
Are you a child spiritually?

12:53.802 --> 12:58.527
Are you able to stick out the disciplines of the Christian life?

12:59.948 --> 13:05.714
Do you jump from this particular Christian community to the next Christian community because I gotta find the most exciting one?

13:06.594 --> 13:09.518
Do you get real bummed out when God doesn't come through with miracles all the time?

13:10.820 --> 13:12.662
Do you need special effects in your life?

13:15.005 --> 13:19.191
Do you need a ring master, or are you willing to listen to people who just simply teach the word of God to you?

13:20.392 --> 13:21.434
Children are unstable.

13:22.295 --> 13:24.818
Children, secondly, are self-centered.

13:25.319 --> 13:27.261
Children, thirdly, have short attention spans.

13:27.762 --> 13:29.865
One more, and then we move out of here.

13:30.526 --> 13:33.810
Children are gullible, very gullible.

13:34.082 --> 13:38.307
I mean, look, I know that these are all, this is a slight oversimplification.

13:38.347 --> 13:43.574
Sometimes children are more discerning than adults for various reasons, but by and large children are gullible.

13:44.555 --> 13:51.304
I was reading Calvin and Hobbes the other day, and Calvin says to his child, I said to his father, Dad, where does the sun go?

13:51.324 --> 13:53.727
He says, well, the sun at night sets in the West.

13:54.388 --> 13:55.509
Where in the West, Dad?

13:57.131 --> 13:58.293
It's around Phoenix.

13:58.393 --> 13:59.414
It sets around Phoenix.

13:59.434 --> 14:02.418
That's why it's so hot out there, and everything's a desert and so on.

14:02.882 --> 14:06.788
And Calvin says, well, then how does it get over here and come up in the east?

14:06.988 --> 14:08.771
Well, they put it on a truck and they drive it all night.

14:09.472 --> 14:17.564
And so, you know, Calvin goes to bed and he says to mom, he says to mom, I hope I'm as smart as dad when I grow up and children are gullible.

14:19.087 --> 14:29.202
Now, the fact is, you have no idea, listen, if you don't know how little you know about the Christian faith, how little you know about the Bible, how gullible you are, you are a child.

14:29.826 --> 14:33.592
You see, you know you're starting to grow out of childhood when you realize how little you know.

14:35.755 --> 14:39.360
I remember when I went to seminary, I was still a fairly new Christian.

14:40.001 --> 14:40.682
Had a professor.

14:40.702 --> 14:42.585
I can't imitate him.

14:42.605 --> 14:45.970
He was Swiss, and he was French Swiss, so I can't imitate his French accent.

14:45.990 --> 14:47.853
But he was a very, very wise man.

14:47.973 --> 14:56.466
And I went to seminary back when, at the time, in the early 70s, when so many of the students who went to seminary were fairly new Christians, and we thought we knew everything.

14:56.738 --> 15:00.623
We would read a book and we would say, aha, now I've grasped that.

15:00.643 --> 15:04.988
And hardly anybody in the history of the Christian churches understood this, but I have understood it.

15:05.648 --> 15:16.741
And so we would come into these theology classes, and Dr. Nicole was so, so loving, and he was so kind, but he was so devastating, because we would get up and say, well, the Bible teaches that.

15:16.761 --> 15:20.626
I'm quite a Bible student, and I know this and that, and I've read this book.

15:20.834 --> 15:31.165
And I've gone to this church, and this minister says this and that, and he's brilliant, and I'm very happy with him, and this has made a difference in Dr. Nicole would say, well, it's very interesting.

15:31.225 --> 15:35.790
I'm sure there's many advantages to that particular set of beliefs.

15:36.371 --> 15:50.546
Now, you should know that in the sixth century, all of Christendom condemned that particular belief as a heresy, and all of the people who ever subscribed and followed that belief for the next 200 years made complete shipwreck of their lives and their families,

15:50.754 --> 15:51.695
and their faith and everything.

15:52.276 --> 16:00.309
Here's three books on this subject that you probably should read that would help you understand this, and you would just realize, I'm a babe.

16:01.731 --> 16:02.572
I don't know that much.

16:04.335 --> 16:09.863
I've never seen a more gullible spiritually, a more gullible group of people than the residents of New York City.

16:11.386 --> 16:19.378
The more dynamic a minister is, the more dynamic a book is, the more exciting an event is, and people just flock, they're gullible.

16:21.218 --> 16:22.379
It sets around Phoenix.

16:23.100 --> 16:23.481
Really?

16:24.722 --> 16:25.503
How does it get there?

16:25.543 --> 16:31.850
Do you know how to read the New York op-ed pages through a biblical grid?

16:32.331 --> 16:34.473
Do you know how to say, well, what's the Bible got to say about this?

16:34.493 --> 16:35.434
Do you know how to critique it?

16:36.075 --> 16:43.924
Can you just pick a book off the book stand and say, well, how does this fit in with biblical themes and with a biblical worldview?

16:43.944 --> 16:44.524
Can you do that?

16:45.245 --> 16:46.927
Do you know how long it takes to be able to do that?

16:48.169 --> 16:49.490
Why do we need to grow?

16:50.274 --> 16:56.700
because of our instability, because of our self-centeredness, because of our superficiality, because of our gullibility.

16:57.001 --> 16:58.042
That's the typical church.

16:59.363 --> 17:02.586
That's also true, I would say, by and large, of the typical congregation.

17:02.606 --> 17:05.249
That's also true of our congregation, by and large.

17:05.849 --> 17:07.491
I'm not mad about it, I'm not even scolding it.

17:07.831 --> 17:09.113
Everybody starts off as kids.

17:09.653 --> 17:14.238
The only thing that would be absolutely ridiculous is for you not to know what you are.

17:14.278 --> 17:18.642
If we don't know what we are, if we don't know how to grow,

17:19.042 --> 17:22.407
If we don't know we have to grow, then we absolutely won't.

17:22.427 --> 17:23.609
That's why we must grow.

17:24.310 --> 17:24.831
We're babies.

17:26.013 --> 17:26.974
We all start that way.

17:27.535 --> 17:29.438
Number two, why?

17:29.458 --> 17:30.760
Okay, now what?

17:31.481 --> 17:32.482
Into what do we grow?

17:32.502 --> 17:35.567
Now it says, grow up into your salvation.

17:36.288 --> 17:37.630
Let's be more specific than that.

17:38.251 --> 17:39.273
Where do you get the standard?

17:39.914 --> 17:44.380
In verse 22, it says, now that you have purified yourselves by obeying the truth.

17:44.701 --> 17:45.522
Ah, there we go.

17:46.274 --> 17:49.940
We're supposed to be aiming for purity, but even so, that's an abstraction.

17:50.661 --> 17:55.109
Does the Bible give us a nice concrete way to evaluate purity?

17:56.892 --> 17:58.034
And the answer is, of course.

17:58.875 --> 18:02.001
And in Colossians 1, verse 28, Paul says it this way.

18:02.842 --> 18:08.612
He says his ministry is, quote, so that we may present everyone perfect in Christ.

18:09.353 --> 18:12.178
Or, best of all, Ephesians 4, 13.

18:12.322 --> 18:24.169
Paul says, until we become mature, see there's the biological analogy, but now he defines it, until we become mature attaining to the measure of the stature of the fullness of Christ.

18:24.189 --> 18:27.798
Now, that's what's so exciting about Christianity.

18:28.218 --> 18:31.506
Christianity does not say grow up into some kind of abstraction.

18:31.714 --> 18:41.875
It doesn't say, grow up into some kind of abstract purity, grow up into some kind of nirvana, some kind of force field, grow up into some kind of high state of consciousness, whatever the heck that is.

18:41.935 --> 18:48.268
It says, look at Jesus, flesh and blood human being, and really look.

18:48.749 --> 18:53.458
One of the things I love about studying the book of Mark, like a lot of us have been doing this year in our small groups,

18:53.666 --> 18:55.208
Mark doesn't give you a lot of talk.

18:55.328 --> 18:57.191
It tells you what Jesus was like.

18:57.211 --> 18:58.313
It just shows you Jesus.

18:58.333 --> 19:00.536
It doesn't give you a whole lot of theological exposition.

19:00.556 --> 19:01.457
It just shows you Jesus.

19:01.898 --> 19:06.545
And when you look at him, he's constantly surprising you.

19:07.286 --> 19:12.494
I'm realizing now it's the surprises that a perfect person affords to imperfect observers.

19:13.075 --> 19:16.440
Everything he does is counterintuitive until it's over and then it makes perfect sense.

19:16.920 --> 19:17.581
He's perfect.

19:18.182 --> 19:19.524
And when you look at him, what have you got?

19:20.145 --> 19:23.570
You see virtues in him combined

19:24.194 --> 19:27.219
that have never, ever anywhere else been combined.

19:28.120 --> 19:37.775
You have tenderness without any weakness and yet you have strength without the slightest gram of harshness.

19:38.676 --> 19:47.870
You have, here's the most amazing to me, you have humility, tremendous humility without one ounce of a lack of self-confidence.

19:48.431 --> 19:49.112
How does he do that?

19:49.793 --> 19:52.818
You've got holiness and unbending convictions

19:53.026 --> 19:55.889
and complete and utter approachability.

19:57.110 --> 20:01.354
You've got power without the slightest insensitivity.

20:01.694 --> 20:04.637
You've got passion without the slightest bit of prejudice.

20:04.857 --> 20:08.501
You've got total integrity and yet without any rigidity.

20:10.703 --> 20:11.624
Never on thinking.

20:12.965 --> 20:14.066
Never a false word.

20:15.548 --> 20:16.528
Never a misstep.

20:17.790 --> 20:18.630
What have you got there?

20:19.551 --> 20:20.472
Moral glory.

20:21.033 --> 20:22.354
Absolute beauty.

20:24.418 --> 20:27.782
Jesus was the most influential man to ever walk the earth.

20:28.383 --> 20:33.229
And his story has been told through books, movies, and articles in hundreds of different ways.

20:33.770 --> 20:35.311
Can anything more be said about him?

20:36.112 --> 20:43.762
In his book, Jesus the King, Tim Keller journeys through the gospel of Mark to reveal how the life of Jesus helps us make sense of our lives.

20:44.383 --> 20:53.554
Dr. Keller shows us how the story of Jesus is at once cosmic, historical, and personal, calling each of us to take a fresh look at our relationship with God.

20:53.794 --> 21:03.689
During the month of March, we'll send you a copy of Jesus the King as our thanks for your gift to help Gospel and Life share the transforming love of Christ with people all over the world.

21:04.330 --> 21:07.535
So request your copy today at gospelandlife.com.

21:07.856 --> 21:10.240
That's gospelandlife.com.

21:10.600 --> 21:14.386
Now here's Dr. Keller with the remainder of today's teaching.

21:17.282 --> 21:22.832
When you look at the human Jesus Christ depicted in the Gospels, it's a lot like looking at the sun through a filter.

21:22.852 --> 21:29.203
You know, you can put a filter so you can look at the sun and you can see the outlines of the sun without it killing your eyes.

21:29.824 --> 21:37.137
And when you look at the human Jesus Christ, what you've actually got is you're looking at God, the divine grandeur through a human nature.

21:37.197 --> 21:42.386
And Paul has the audacity to say, you can grow up into that.

21:43.042 --> 21:45.826
into the fullness of the measure of the stature of Christ.

21:46.367 --> 21:48.269
That's what we're out for, nothing less.

21:48.329 --> 21:55.079
And that's why Peter says here, the only way you can do this, this is verse 23, how can you grow like this?

21:55.139 --> 21:57.482
How can you have yourselves purified by obeying the truth?

21:57.802 --> 21:58.824
We saw this several weeks ago.

21:59.304 --> 22:03.390
For you have been born again, not of perishable seed, but imperishable seed.

22:04.351 --> 22:05.633
What's the imperishable seed?

22:06.534 --> 22:09.298
Imperishable, that means eternal, immortal.

22:09.538 --> 22:11.581
Some kind of stuff He calls it a sea.

22:11.641 --> 22:13.404
Some kind of substance has come on in.

22:14.806 --> 22:15.447
What came in?

22:16.188 --> 22:16.769
You know what it is?

22:17.711 --> 22:19.133
One way to put it is the Holy Spirit.

22:20.195 --> 22:21.677
We've told that many, many places.

22:22.178 --> 22:32.574
But in John chapter 17, He says, when I send the Holy Spirit, John chapter 16, John chapter 15 and 14 actually, all through there, Jesus says, I'm going to send you the Holy Spirit and I will come into you.

22:32.594 --> 22:35.058
And what He means is the Holy Spirit

22:35.170 --> 22:37.052
When you become a Christian, enters into you.

22:37.092 --> 22:37.553
What is that?

22:37.913 --> 22:40.757
It's Jesus Christ's spiritual DNA.

22:43.501 --> 22:44.922
It's his spiritual DNA.

22:45.563 --> 22:47.766
Best thing I can, that's what we can talk about.

22:47.786 --> 22:49.648
The divine nature, Peter calls it.

22:50.690 --> 22:56.577
And what it means to grow in Christ is not what it means to kind of build your body up.

22:56.617 --> 23:00.402
You go to the workout center and you've got certain goals and you've got certain regimens.

23:00.514 --> 23:01.756
We're talking about something else.

23:02.156 --> 23:09.625
We're talking about the spiritual DNA of Jesus Christ coming into your life and unfolding until you reach the fullness of the Statue of Christ.

23:10.627 --> 23:11.968
That's what we're talking about.

23:12.209 --> 23:13.811
That's what we're supposed to grow up into.

23:14.151 --> 23:17.916
And therefore, before we move on to the last point, what are we saying?

23:18.336 --> 23:19.378
What are we growing up into?

23:21.060 --> 23:25.365
The fullness of the Statue of Christ because we have the imperishable seed in us.

23:25.906 --> 23:29.330
Now, just before we leave, let me just press this home for a second.

23:30.466 --> 23:35.652
Again, the Bible is so much more complex than the alternatives.

23:35.992 --> 23:38.495
The Christian message is so much more complex than the alternatives.

23:38.856 --> 23:53.072
Whenever you read in the Bible saying, love one another, be honest, live decently, live moral, it always, always, always is assuming that the people you're talking to have the imperishable seed.

23:54.173 --> 23:57.136
In other words, the Bible never really says to anybody, live a good life.

23:57.236 --> 23:58.738
It says, grow up.

23:59.330 --> 24:01.772
into the fullness of the measure of the stature of Christ.

24:02.093 --> 24:03.774
That's a far more complex command.

24:04.275 --> 24:10.941
It doesn't mean, you see, if you are a Christian, if you've got that imperishable seat, it does mean tomorrow you have a temptation to lie.

24:11.262 --> 24:12.283
You say, no, I'm not going to lie.

24:12.303 --> 24:13.104
I'm going to tell the truth.

24:13.424 --> 24:15.986
So there's a volitional element.

24:16.006 --> 24:18.469
There is a sense in which you say, OK, I'm going to do right.

24:19.850 --> 24:27.698
But the Bible always assumes, always, when it says love, be honest, whenever it lays down its ethical prescriptions, it always assumes

24:29.218 --> 24:30.680
that you have that imperishable seed.

24:31.421 --> 24:38.792
Being a Christian is not, it never has been, simply lifting up, picking up a set of moral principles and saying, I'm going to live like this.

24:40.174 --> 24:42.598
If that's what you think Christianity is, you are not a Christian.

24:43.319 --> 24:46.423
A Christian is someone whose center has been dealt with, has been shaken.

24:47.465 --> 24:49.328
Some new radical principle has come in.

24:49.388 --> 24:50.850
The imperishable seed.

24:51.110 --> 24:53.714
That's why it says, you're born again by imperishable seed.

24:53.834 --> 24:56.338
Otherwise, the Bible says, until you have that,

24:56.770 --> 24:59.194
None of our ethical prescriptions will really help you.

24:59.896 --> 25:01.138
They're too hard for you.

25:01.178 --> 25:02.140
They won't work for you.

25:02.160 --> 25:03.222
You won't understand them.

25:03.603 --> 25:04.464
You'll misuse them.

25:04.484 --> 25:10.896
You'll see them as a ladder to get to God instead of the outworking of the salvation and the grace that God's already given you.

25:11.196 --> 25:12.258
You won't understand anything.

25:12.278 --> 25:18.610
And therefore, some of you are trying to get help in a piecemeal way.

25:19.106 --> 25:32.039
You might become into church or you might come to Christianity because you're having a hard time in your life or you've got a habit you're trying to deal with or you've got a bad patch you're trying to get over and you're coming to church or you come to Christianity for a little bit of inspiration or help.

25:32.359 --> 25:32.839
Forget it.

25:34.541 --> 25:39.766
The Bible never says change here, do this, you know, buck up, live a little better life.

25:39.806 --> 25:43.170
The Bible says you must be born by imperishable seed.

25:43.210 --> 25:47.794
You must be radically and completely remade and rebuilt from the ground up.

25:48.610 --> 25:55.760
You must get a new center, a new heart, a new principle in you, a new DNA spiritually that unfolds.

25:56.701 --> 25:58.283
That is what Christianity is about.

25:58.323 --> 26:02.189
Thirdly, why do we have to grow?

26:02.209 --> 26:06.615
Because we're stupid, because we're babies, because we're infantile.

26:07.596 --> 26:08.737
What are we growing up into?

26:08.777 --> 26:14.866
Not just some abstract nirvana, not some kind of cosmic consciousness, but the fullness of the measure of the stature of Christ.

26:15.867 --> 26:17.970
Thirdly and lastly, how do we grow?

26:18.274 --> 26:23.360
What you have here are three principles that I'll give you an overview of.

26:23.380 --> 26:28.145
I think I mentioned last week that years ago I heard a talk by J.I.

26:28.185 --> 26:28.545
Packer.

26:28.565 --> 26:33.030
I heard him in person and he laid down three principles and he gave them names.

26:34.011 --> 26:35.293
And the three principles are here.

26:36.234 --> 26:37.535
And he says, you will never grow.

26:37.956 --> 26:40.038
You will never let that DNA move on.

26:40.999 --> 26:44.843
You will never grow up in the fullness of the stature of Christ unless you do these three things.

26:44.863 --> 26:45.224
And they're here.

26:45.544 --> 26:47.346
And here's what they are.

26:47.586 --> 26:54.357
Number one, the way of acceptance, the way of acceptance.

26:54.377 --> 27:07.698
When he says to it, well, if you want to see where it is, it's in verse 22, now that you have purified your cells by obeying, by obeying.

27:09.282 --> 27:11.525
Years ago, back in the 40s, when C.S.

27:11.586 --> 27:19.919
Lewis did his radio talks that became Mayor Christianity, he said, there's really only three basic worldviews vying for the hearts of people today.

27:19.959 --> 27:22.903
Three basic worldviews out there in the marketplace of ideas.

27:23.464 --> 27:26.729
He said there were theism, naturalism, and pantheism.

27:27.510 --> 27:37.586
And without trying to go into too much detail, just enough to give you the outlines, theism, of course, is the idea of the biblical God, a personal God,

27:37.698 --> 27:47.808
A God you can pray to, a holy God, a God that can be known, a God who speaks, a God who gives the law, there's heaven and hell, and so on.

27:47.868 --> 27:48.469
That's theism.

27:49.690 --> 27:52.352
Naturalism, by naturalism, he means secularism.

27:52.673 --> 27:57.497
The idea that all we really have here, all that really exists, is matter.

27:58.298 --> 27:59.800
All that really exists is nature.

27:59.960 --> 28:01.201
That's why you call it naturalism.

28:01.682 --> 28:06.226
All that really exists is what you can taste, touch, hear, see, or smell.

28:06.434 --> 28:07.556
There is no spirit world.

28:07.816 --> 28:08.738
There is no soul.

28:08.958 --> 28:09.980
There is no afterlife.

28:10.381 --> 28:11.402
When you die, you rot.

28:11.963 --> 28:16.871
There is no meaning or morality other than what you find in your own feelings, period.

28:17.632 --> 28:29.392
Pantheism, on the other hand, was the Eastern religions, and you see it in Hinduism and Buddhism in the New Age religions, and pantheism says there's no personal God, but there's a kind of life force that's out there.

28:29.432 --> 28:33.138
And it's in everything, and we are part of it.

28:33.858 --> 28:38.963
And whereas naturalism says the only thing that's real is the material.

28:39.964 --> 28:41.285
Everything else is just an illusion.

28:42.806 --> 28:48.291
Eastern pantheism, the New Age stuff actually says the only thing that's real is the spiritual.

28:49.453 --> 28:50.433
Matter is an illusion.

28:50.934 --> 28:52.135
This world is an illusion.

28:52.155 --> 28:58.041
And so they say, you see, the language of the New Age theology is therefore create your own reality.

28:58.581 --> 28:59.262
You are God.

28:59.762 --> 29:03.826
The limitations you perceive out there are actually illusions.

29:04.354 --> 29:06.016
Anything you want can happen.

29:06.296 --> 29:08.118
Anything you really believe in can be.

29:08.418 --> 29:09.259
See, that's the language.

29:09.279 --> 29:12.001
It's real heady kind of language, but again, don't you see?

29:12.982 --> 29:14.724
Naturalism and pantheism.

29:14.744 --> 29:17.066
Naturalism says only the material world is real.

29:18.087 --> 29:19.949
Pantheism says only the spiritual world is real.

29:19.989 --> 29:20.510
See the problem?

29:20.630 --> 29:21.411
They're both too easy.

29:22.912 --> 29:23.893
But here's my point.

29:24.454 --> 29:33.042
In both cases, as different as they are, and many times they fight with each other, as different as they seem to be, they always agree on one thing.

29:33.378 --> 29:34.960
There's no such thing as obedience.

29:36.962 --> 29:38.924
How do you decide what is right and wrong for you?

29:38.984 --> 29:40.826
Well, the naturalist says, well, there is no right and wrong.

29:40.846 --> 29:42.508
You just sort of look and see what your feelings are.

29:42.528 --> 29:43.529
You make your own.

29:44.490 --> 29:47.313
How do you decide what is right and wrong says to the new age person?

29:47.714 --> 29:49.936
The new age person says, well, you have to look inside.

29:50.016 --> 29:53.360
And Luke, you have to reach out with your feelings.

29:53.440 --> 29:57.825
Luke, you have to figure out what your heart really wants.

29:59.266 --> 30:02.610
Only Christianity has a way of acceptance.

30:02.786 --> 30:04.608
And this is one of the reasons why someone popular.

30:05.228 --> 30:07.991
The way of acceptance is obedience.

30:08.011 --> 30:14.878
There is something outside of your heart, says Christianity, and that something outside of your heart is a standard.

30:14.918 --> 30:15.759
It's the law of God.

30:16.219 --> 30:17.200
It's the Word of God.

30:17.340 --> 30:18.261
It's the will of God.

30:18.341 --> 30:19.542
It's outside of you.

30:20.664 --> 30:21.845
And you must submit to it.

30:22.265 --> 30:23.747
Here's what the way of acceptance is.

30:23.767 --> 30:28.351
It's to look at God and to say, not my will, but thine be done.

30:28.391 --> 30:31.314
You cannot grow.

30:31.938 --> 30:33.200
You will always be a baby.

30:33.560 --> 30:35.763
You will never grow up into the fullness of the stature of Christ.

30:36.804 --> 30:39.868
Unless you can say, not my will, but thine be done.

30:40.408 --> 30:42.010
The way of acceptance.

30:42.030 --> 30:42.311
Where?

30:42.451 --> 30:44.193
Well, let me give you just three real quick.

30:44.253 --> 30:45.975
Three areas where the way of acceptance works.

30:46.315 --> 30:49.039
Number one, God's law.

30:49.660 --> 30:51.262
God's law says a few things that are hard.

30:51.802 --> 30:53.084
It says you must always forgive.

30:54.886 --> 31:01.554
It says you must be radically generous with your money and not live as well as you could live, but give away so much of your money, it lowers your lifestyle.

31:01.954 --> 31:03.816
be that generous.

31:03.836 --> 31:06.540
It says, you must never twist the truth to look good.

31:07.761 --> 31:16.792
It says, you must never use sex as something that gives you pleasure but always as an expression of a permanent, exclusive covenant with somebody else.

31:16.812 --> 31:22.739
So he says, you know, you sex in that way and never return evil for evil and always be generous and never twist the truth to look good.

31:22.759 --> 31:23.360
Those are hard.

31:23.380 --> 31:23.820
What is that?

31:24.201 --> 31:25.202
You have to obey.

31:25.762 --> 31:32.629
You don't look inside yourself and say, hmm, well, it looks like I should never, my heart says never, ever, ever twist the truth to look good, never lie.

31:32.689 --> 31:33.831
Your heart will not say that.

31:36.173 --> 31:38.035
How will you even get an idea of honesty?

31:38.836 --> 31:41.539
He has where naturalism and pantheism make absolutely no sense at all.

31:42.100 --> 31:44.262
How will you even get an idea of honesty unless you look outside?

31:44.302 --> 31:47.706
The way of acceptance, you have to accept what God says is right.

31:49.127 --> 31:51.490
Oh, secondly, give me another example.

31:51.850 --> 31:53.572
You have to accept God's evaluation of you.

31:54.133 --> 31:55.474
You know what the gospel is.

31:55.874 --> 31:56.555
Let's say it again.

31:56.615 --> 32:08.528
The gospel is, on the one hand, you are far more evil and wicked than you ever dared believe, but because Jesus died for you, you are more loved and accepted than you ever dared hope at the same time.

32:09.950 --> 32:11.371
Now, that's an evaluation of you.

32:11.431 --> 32:12.232
Have you accepted it?

32:12.713 --> 32:15.976
On the one hand, it says, you are a wicked, helpless sinner.

32:16.817 --> 32:18.058
Do you get offended by that?

32:18.078 --> 32:20.381
I know some of you are saying, you're kidding.

32:20.421 --> 32:22.704
Somebody with more than a third grade education really believes that?

32:23.184 --> 32:24.946
You know, there's pride.

32:25.314 --> 32:28.278
and you have not accepted God's assessment of you.

32:28.738 --> 32:31.201
But on the other hand, there's the second half of the gospel.

32:31.582 --> 32:34.966
He loves you more than you ever dared hope or believe.

32:35.607 --> 32:38.190
There's many of you who think that you're junk.

32:38.491 --> 32:40.253
There's many of you who hate yourself.

32:40.493 --> 32:43.117
And yet here's God saying, look what I've done for you.

32:43.537 --> 32:44.659
Look who I've sent for you.

32:45.059 --> 32:47.722
Look what I have, look how I've poured myself out for you.

32:48.023 --> 32:50.326
Look, you're engraved on the palm of my hands.

32:52.088 --> 32:53.650
What are you doing down there?

32:54.242 --> 32:56.084
Why are you treating yourself like this?

32:57.306 --> 32:59.969
Do you see what it means to submit the way of acceptance?

33:00.330 --> 33:03.814
Are you willing to admit and accept what he says about your sin?

33:04.215 --> 33:06.237
Are you willing to admit how much he loves you?

33:07.018 --> 33:10.903
Some of you won't do either, but certainly most of you will only do one.

33:10.943 --> 33:14.988
And unless you do both, you haven't found the way of acceptance.

33:16.090 --> 33:17.972
Well, I gotta keep going, gotta finish up here.

33:18.233 --> 33:22.578
The way of acceptance, the second major way that you grow

33:22.722 --> 33:23.743
is the way of nourishment.

33:23.803 --> 33:28.368
Look, as newborn babes crave the pure spiritual milk.

33:29.089 --> 33:32.473
Now, the pure spiritual milk is fairly simple to see.

33:32.933 --> 33:38.139
Many times in the Bible, the word of God is seen as food, or the word of God is seen as milk.

33:38.920 --> 33:43.364
Like in Hebrews 5, it says, the most elementary principles of God's word are milk.

33:44.185 --> 33:48.530
And what you have here is that he says, make sure

33:48.706 --> 33:49.767
that you take it in.

33:49.847 --> 33:51.609
Milk is food.

33:51.669 --> 33:52.570
Take it in.

33:52.870 --> 33:53.450
What does that mean?

33:53.751 --> 33:54.191
Just this.

33:56.213 --> 33:58.695
How do you eat?

33:59.296 --> 33:59.816
Three things.

34:00.297 --> 34:02.039
Number one, you cut the food up.

34:02.599 --> 34:07.023
You get it into a condition which it can go into your mouth.

34:07.904 --> 34:10.427
Two, you taste it and chew it up.

34:11.147 --> 34:15.952
And three, you swallow it and digest it and it becomes part of you.

34:17.193 --> 34:18.354
The way of nourishment

34:18.594 --> 34:20.677
It means, number one, you've got to believe the Bible.

34:20.717 --> 34:24.842
That means you have to at least trust it enough that you're willing to really take it in.

34:25.623 --> 34:32.291
But the first step, cutting it up is like study, interpreting it, understanding it so you can take it in.

34:32.331 --> 34:32.932
But that's not enough.

34:32.952 --> 34:33.773
You have to taste it.

34:34.493 --> 34:36.436
You have to turn it over on the palate of your heart.

34:36.976 --> 34:38.238
You have to let it melt your heart.

34:38.739 --> 34:41.963
You have to let the truth that you're looking at lead you to pray.

34:41.983 --> 34:42.563
Do you do that?

34:43.364 --> 34:44.786
And then you have to apply it.

34:44.866 --> 34:45.787
You have to digest it.

34:46.067 --> 34:49.671
You have to make it part of the deep structures of your psyche and of your life.

34:51.372 --> 34:56.798
You've got to say, if I take this truth seriously, how does it make a difference in the way I am going to live today?

34:56.838 --> 34:59.280
I'm going to be doing this with somebody.

34:59.300 --> 35:00.982
I'm going to be doing this with somebody.

35:01.042 --> 35:01.602
How?

35:01.622 --> 35:05.686
If I take this seriously, how will this truth have an impact on the way in which I live?

35:05.906 --> 35:06.947
That's digestion.

35:07.007 --> 35:09.770
Interpretation, meditation, application.

35:09.830 --> 35:12.373
You have to cut the food.

35:12.393 --> 35:13.874
You have to taste the food.

35:14.210 --> 35:15.812
And you have to digest the food.

35:15.832 --> 35:16.714
Are you doing all of it?

35:18.136 --> 35:20.580
Otherwise, you're not following the way of nourishment.

35:21.221 --> 35:23.003
And of course, that takes a great deal of discipline.

35:23.404 --> 35:26.088
The Word of God has to come on in.

35:26.489 --> 35:30.895
It says, John chapter 15, let my words abide in you.

35:30.995 --> 35:33.800
Colossians 3, let the Word of God dwell in you richly.

35:33.840 --> 35:34.781
You've got to take it in.

35:34.821 --> 35:36.343
You've got to saturate your mind in it.

35:36.364 --> 35:37.906
You've got to dream through it.

35:39.548 --> 35:41.071
It's got to be that much a part of you.

35:41.371 --> 35:43.314
It's got to be part of your mental furniture.

35:45.154 --> 35:48.998
Okay, lastly, and this is last, the way of exchange.

35:49.538 --> 35:52.421
The way of acceptance, see, purified by obedience.

35:52.981 --> 35:56.645
The way of nourishment, take in the pure spiritual milk.

35:56.725 --> 36:02.430
And lastly, the way of exchange, which is love one another sincerely and love one another deeply.

36:02.771 --> 36:06.054
And since we spend a whole evening on that, I'm only going to mention it in a word.

36:06.634 --> 36:09.577
You cannot grow on your own.

36:10.158 --> 36:11.779
There's got to be relationships.

36:12.620 --> 36:14.962
You have no idea what you really look like.

36:15.042 --> 36:26.756
Haven't you ever noticed that unless you're somebody who's constantly getting up on stage or something, whenever you see yourself in a video, whenever you hear yourself on a tape, don't you go, oh, gosh.

36:28.799 --> 36:30.501
I don't really look like that, do I?

36:30.922 --> 36:32.944
I don't really sound like that, do I?

36:33.245 --> 36:36.388
And all the people around you go, yes, you do.

36:37.049 --> 36:38.211
Yes, you do.

36:38.952 --> 36:40.093
That's exactly how you look.

36:40.473 --> 36:41.775
That's exactly how you sound.

36:42.536 --> 36:43.077
What is that?

36:43.357 --> 36:44.178
That's fellowship.

36:46.818 --> 36:48.520
There is no way you will know yourself.

36:48.780 --> 36:52.245
There is no way you will know your strengths or your weaknesses.

36:52.405 --> 36:56.269
There is no way you will see your greatest flaws.

36:57.070 --> 37:01.596
Don't you understand your greatest flaw has got to be today, the one you see the least.

37:02.537 --> 37:03.618
That's why it's your greatest.

37:03.939 --> 37:05.240
It's the one that has the most power over you.

37:05.681 --> 37:07.423
It's the one that you are the most unconscious of.

37:07.683 --> 37:08.625
You're never going to see it.

37:09.045 --> 37:10.186
You've got to have other people around you.

37:10.226 --> 37:14.131
You've got to have decent people around you, people who love you sincerely and who love you deeply.

37:14.372 --> 37:15.132
You will never grow.

37:15.152 --> 37:16.434
You'll always stay a baby.

37:16.770 --> 37:27.148
And that's the reason why some of you, in spite of the fact that you have done a lot of the way of acceptance and a lot of the way of nourishment because you are lone rangers, because you're mavericks, because you're loners, you haven't really grown much.

37:28.110 --> 37:34.541
The way of acceptance, the way of nourishment and the way of exchange.

37:34.622 --> 37:35.122
But you know what?

37:35.343 --> 37:36.204
Here's the greatest thing.

37:36.745 --> 37:37.907
You notice where it all comes from?

37:38.208 --> 37:39.410
You know what motivates it?

37:39.618 --> 37:47.967
It says, as newborn babes, crave the pure spiritual milk so that you may grow up into your salvation, now that you have tasted that the Lord is good.

37:51.191 --> 37:53.873
The word goodness, God's goodness is His grace.

37:54.895 --> 38:00.941
God's goodness is the fact, and this is the gospel, that you are not saved because of your good deeds.

38:01.862 --> 38:05.426
You were saved and accepted because of what Jesus Christ did for you on the cross.

38:05.826 --> 38:15.460
And therefore, the moment you believe, the moment you become a Christian, God legally takes away your sin and legally adopts you into his family.

38:16.621 --> 38:19.625
Now, that grace cannot be increased.

38:21.488 --> 38:22.950
Your status can't increase.

38:22.970 --> 38:25.634
You can't be more accepted than you are the first minute you become a Christian.

38:25.914 --> 38:30.320
But your experience of that goodness, your experience of that grace can increase.

38:31.101 --> 38:32.023
And that's the idea.

38:32.063 --> 38:34.386
That tasting means the experience of it.

38:35.010 --> 38:37.234
Why is it that you want to grow?

38:37.274 --> 38:41.622
Not because you hope God might be good to you.

38:41.643 --> 38:46.592
That's the great way to become a monk in a bad sense of the word.

38:46.652 --> 38:48.215
That's a great way to become an ascetic.

38:48.255 --> 38:58.354
That's a great way to become someone who is trying to purify yourself, hoping that maybe God will open the gates of heaven, hoping that other people will see that you're really a good person.

38:58.434 --> 38:59.776
That's not why you're supposed to be doing it.

38:59.796 --> 39:02.199
You're not doing it because you hope the gut will be good.

39:02.459 --> 39:05.002
You have to be doing it because you've already tasted that he is good.

39:05.423 --> 39:06.063
Have you done that?

39:08.887 --> 39:09.648
Are you growing?

39:09.808 --> 39:10.749
Are you really changing?

39:11.110 --> 39:12.071
Are you really becoming?

39:13.993 --> 39:15.455
Are you more patient than you were last year?

39:15.495 --> 39:16.837
Ask somebody who knows you.

39:17.978 --> 39:19.520
Are you less worried than you were last year?

39:19.560 --> 39:20.761
Ask somebody who knows you.

39:20.821 --> 39:26.028
Are you able to take criticism better than last year?

39:26.068 --> 39:27.890
Ask somebody who knows you.

39:28.738 --> 39:30.320
Come on, let's get practical about this.

39:30.420 --> 39:33.104
And if not, taste and see that the Lord is good.

39:34.345 --> 39:34.726
Let's pray.

39:35.326 --> 39:39.632
We thank you, Lord, that you have given us this message and this truth.

39:40.433 --> 39:47.041
Help us to taste your goodness until we grow up into your salvation of the measure of the stature of the fullness of Christ.

39:47.081 --> 39:49.064
In Jesus' name we pray, amen.

39:54.251 --> 39:56.914
Thanks for joining us here on the Gospel and Life podcast.

39:57.154 --> 40:02.440
If you were encouraged by today's teaching, you can help others discover this podcast by rating and reviewing it.

40:02.861 --> 40:07.706
And to find more great gospel-centered content by Tim Keller, visit gospelandlife.com.

40:08.868 --> 40:10.670
Today's sermon was recorded in 1993.

40:10.870 --> 40:21.202
The sermons and talks you hear on the Gospel and Life podcast were recorded between 1989 and 2017, while Dr. Keller was senior pastor at Redeemer Presbyterian Church.

